rn, something at once intimate, indispensable and elusive; something we take for granted and yet remains difficult to pin down, describe or define. This volume of twelve essays explores how writers in different domains – philosophers and thinkers, novelists, poets, churchmen, political writers and others – construed, fashioned and expressed the self in written form in Great Britain in the course of the long eighteenth century from the Restoration to the period of the French Revolution. The essays are preceded by an introduction that seeks to frame several key aspects of the debate on the self in a succinct and open-minded spirit. The volume foregrounds the coming into being of a recognisably modern self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSelf (Philosophy). 0aSelf in literature. 0aSelf. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aJohn Locke.  aconsciousness.  aindividual.  aindividualism.  along eighteenth century.  apersonal identity.  asecularisation.  aself-fashioning.  aself-love.  athe long eighteenth century.  athe self.  athe soul.1 aAlexander, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntal, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBruni Roccia, Gioiella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlesch, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopes, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc